##Special Report | a list of people who don't want to be updated

Hi, Monica and Monica

Function description, here is the "First Finance" magazine (predecessor "first finance weekly") readers club, we discover wonderful business value for you, also invited you to explore the bright business world.

Intern reporter | Yuan Ying

Editor | Xu Shiyu

The epidemic has brought home to people the value of medical resources.

In a sense, to protect health care workers and medical technologists is to protect the lives of others. However, the occupational specificity of health workers means that they are at higher risk of infection in an outbreak.

On February 17th, for the first time, we paid our respects on public log by recording the names of the medical workers who died in the new pneumonia outbreak.

In the new issue of China Business News, we have included and updated this list. Though we had hoped the list would never be updated. But after that, a few more paramedics left us. Meanwhile, as more information is disclosed, more victims'names are added to the relevant lists.

So here we are, updating the list, once again paying tribute to the memory.

Li Wenliang, 34

Li Wenliang, 34

Wuhan Central Hospital ophthalmologist, first-line Doctors Fighting COVID-19 pneumonia, as early as December 30,2019 to the outside world issued a protective alert, known as the "whistle blower. ".

Li Wenliang graduated from the Wuhan University in 2011. He holds a doctor of medicine and is a member of the Hubei Ophthalmology Association. He has participated in scientific research projects of the National Natural Science Foundation of China and the Wuhan University, and has been engaged in clinical work in ophthalmology for many years, good at Fundus disease, cataract, Glaucoma diagnosis and treatment. He is currently working in the Ophthalmology Department of the Wuhan Central Hospital. He has published many papers with high level of SCI, and he has made accurate diagnosis and treatment of common eye diseases, especially difficult ones. He sits for consultation every Saturday and Sunday.

On January 8, he contracted COVID-19 pneumonia after receiving a female patient without special protection. Li developed cough on January 10, developed fever on January 11, was hospitalized on January 12, and was transferred to the intensive-care unit on January 14 due to an aggravated condition. He was treated with antibiotics, hormones, antiviral drugs and high flow oxygen inhalation. On February 1, Li Wenliang was diagnosed as a new case of coronary pneumonia.

At around 9:00 p.m. on February 6, some media released the news that Li Wenliang had died. At the same time, there was also news that Li Wenliang was being rescued by ECMO. At 0:38 p.m. on the 7th, an official of Wuhan Central Hospital released a message saying, dr. Li Wenliang "is critically ill and is doing all he can to save him. ".

Li Wenliang died at Wuhan Central Hospital at 2:58 a.m. on Feb. 7, according to official sources.

Liu Xiaoxian, 83

Professor of the Public Health of the Tongji Medical College, supervisor of Graduate Students, Executive Director of the Chinese Society for Preventive Medicine, Executive Director of the Chinese Society for Preventive Medicine, Executive Director of the Chinese Society for child health care, vice president of the Hubei Society for Management of maternal and child health care, vice president of the Hubei Provincial Society for sexual health care, member of the Advisory Committee of the Chinese Center for Disease Prevention and control, chairman of the Hubei Society for Comprehensive Child Development, chairman of the Wuhan Society for Maternal and Child Health of the Chinese Society for Preventive Medicine, honorary director of the Tongji Medical College, and Chairman of the Academic Committee.

Liu Xiaoxian is the founder of maternal and Child Health Specialty in China's higher education. In 1985, she founded the first undergraduate specialty of maternal and child health in China, which has trained a large number of professional talents for the country and become the backbone of maternal and child health.

Liu Xiaoxian is also the builder of the National Rural Primary Health Care Network. In the 1970s, she chose the old revolutionary base of Macheng as the base, and set up a rural grass-roots three-level maternal and child health care network with birth, death, infectious diseases and tumor as its main contents. In 20 years, she trained a large number of rural doctors, and her work led to Macheng being listed by UNICEF as one of the country's first model counties for maternal and child health.

On February 13, Liu Xiaoxian died in Tongji Hospital in Wuhan after medical treatment failed.

Duan Zhengcheng, 86

Chinese Academy of Engineering, Professor, Huazhong University of Science and Technology, chief scientist, National Engineering Research Center for digital manufacturing equipment, and expert in machine building and automation

In 1996, Duan Zhengcheng combined mechanical science with radiotherapy medicine to develop the first international whole body gamma knife. In 1999, Duan Zhengcheng developed the world's first large-scale radiotherapy equipment, called the total body gamma knife, which can rotate and focus the gamma rays on the tumor after precise positioning, thus killing the tumor cells, greatly reduce the damage to normal tissues and organs of human body. It has been used in more than 100 hospitals nationwide, benefiting nearly one million people.

Professor Duan Zhengcheng, who was diagnosed with COVID-19 pneumonia on January 29 and suffered from underlying diseases such as diabetes, died at 19:35 on February 15 in hospital after medical treatment failed.
